IBADAN – The Oyo State governor, Engr. Seyi Makinde, has said he will announce the name of the new Olubadan of Ibadanland on Monday. Makinde disclosed this on Saturday at the Liberty Stadium, Ibadan, capital city of Oyo State, during the final burial rites of late Oba Saliu Adetunji Ajeoguguniso 1, stressing that the crisis rocking the succession to Olubadan stool had been laid to rest. Makinde said he had received official letter from the Olubadan-in-Council on their choice for the new Olubadan. The governor, in his remark at the state burial for the late Oba Adetunji, said, “We are happy that crisis rocking succession to Olubadan stool have been resolved. New Olubadan will be announced on Monday. Olubadan-in-council has officially written to me.” Green Energy Perfect Plans To Commission LPG Extraction, Power… Mecho Autotech Raises $2.15m For Vehicle Maintenance, Repair… “Olubadan stoll doesn’t need amendments, Ibadan tradition is envious by people, because we are the pace setter.” In his remark, the Central Council of Ibadan Indigenes (CCII), President General, Yemisi Adeaga, described the late monarch as a humble personality during his lifetime, who transformed the town with his wide experience. Speaking on behalf of the Adetunji family, son of the late monarch, Abdul Raheem Adetunji, said his father touched many lives while alive, adding that the family was not mourning, but celebrating a fufilled life of their father. He thanked Governor Makinde for keeping his promise by giving the late monarch befitting burial, pledging the family’s support towards the development of the state. Dignitaries at the event included the deputy governor of the state, Engr. Rauf Olaniyan, ex-Governor Rashidi Ladoja, Sen. Kola Balogun, PDP Deputy National Chairman, Amb. Taofek Arapaja, commissioners, members of State House of Assembly, local government chairmen, and Ibadan sons and daughters, among others.